======================================================================
PART 1: THE CYCLOTOMIC BAER FACTORIZATION
======================================================================

The master identity: Phi_3(x^2) = Phi_3(x) * Phi_6(x)

  q=2: Phi_3(2^2) = Phi_3(4) = 21
       = Phi_3(2) * Phi_6(2) = 7 * 3 = 21  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_4) = 3 copies of PG(2,F_2)

  q=3: Phi_3(3^2) = Phi_3(9) = 91
       = Phi_3(3) * Phi_6(3) = 13 * 7 = 91  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_9) = 7 copies of PG(2,F_3)

  q=4: Phi_3(4^2) = Phi_3(16) = 273
       = Phi_3(4) * Phi_6(4) = 21 * 13 = 273  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_16) = 13 copies of PG(2,F_4)

  q=5: Phi_3(5^2) = Phi_3(25) = 651
       = Phi_3(5) * Phi_6(5) = 31 * 21 = 651  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_25) = 21 copies of PG(2,F_5)

  q=6: Phi_3(6^2) = Phi_3(36) = 1333
       = Phi_3(6) * Phi_6(6) = 43 * 31 = 1333  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_36) = 31 copies of PG(2,F_6)

  q=7: Phi_3(7^2) = Phi_3(49) = 2451
       = Phi_3(7) * Phi_6(7) = 57 * 43 = 2451  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_49) = 43 copies of PG(2,F_7)

  q=8: Phi_3(8^2) = Phi_3(64) = 4161
       = Phi_3(8) * Phi_6(8) = 73 * 57 = 4161  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_64) = 57 copies of PG(2,F_8)

  q=9: Phi_3(9^2) = Phi_3(81) = 6643
       = Phi_3(9) * Phi_6(9) = 91 * 73 = 6643  ✓
       Baer decomposition: PG(2,F_81) = 73 copies of PG(2,F_9)

THE TOURNAMENT INSTANCE (q=2):
  Phi_3(4) = 21 = Phi_3(2) * Phi_6(2) = 7 * 3
  PG(2,F_4) = 3 copies of PG(2,F_2) (Fano planes)
  Phi_3(2) = 7 = Fano plane = K₃ poison = FORBIDDEN H-value 1
  Phi_6(2) = 3 = cycle generator = NUMBER of Baer subplanes
  Their product 21 = FORBIDDEN H-value 2

======================================================================
PART 2: THE SIXTH CYCLOTOMIC STRUCTURE
======================================================================

x^6 - 1 = Phi_1(x) * Phi_2(x) * Phi_3(x) * Phi_6(x)

  x=2: 2^6-1 = 63
       = Phi_1(2) * Phi_2(2) * Phi_3(2) * Phi_6(2)
       = 1 * 3 * 7 * 3 = 63  ✓
  x=3: 3^6-1 = 728
       = Phi_1(3) * Phi_2(3) * Phi_3(3) * Phi_6(3)
       = 2 * 4 * 13 * 7 = 728  ✓
  x=4: 4^6-1 = 4095
       = Phi_1(4) * Phi_2(4) * Phi_3(4) * Phi_6(4)
       = 3 * 5 * 21 * 13 = 4095  ✓
  x=5: 5^6-1 = 15624
       = Phi_1(5) * Phi_2(5) * Phi_3(5) * Phi_6(5)
       = 4 * 6 * 31 * 21 = 15624  ✓
  x=6: 6^6-1 = 46655
       = Phi_1(6) * Phi_2(6) * Phi_3(6) * Phi_6(6)
       = 5 * 7 * 43 * 31 = 46655  ✓
  x=7: 7^6-1 = 117648
       = Phi_1(7) * Phi_2(7) * Phi_3(7) * Phi_6(7)
       = 6 * 8 * 57 * 43 = 117648  ✓

At x=2:
  2^6 - 1 = 63 = 1 * 3 * 7 * 3
  But 1*3*7*3 = 63 ✓
  Phi_3(2) * Phi_6(2) = 7 * 3 = 21 = (2^6-1)/(2^2-1) = 63/3 = 21 ✓

DEEPER: x^4 + x^2 + 1 = Phi_3(x) * Phi_6(x)
This polynomial is the 'Baer polynomial' — it generates the subplane partition.
  x=2: 2^4+2^2+1 = 21 = 7*3 = 21  ✓
  x=3: 3^4+3^2+1 = 91 = 13*7 = 91  ✓
  x=4: 4^4+4^2+1 = 273 = 21*13 = 273  ✓
  x=5: 5^4+5^2+1 = 651 = 31*21 = 651  ✓
  x=6: 6^4+6^2+1 = 1333 = 43*31 = 1333  ✓
  x=7: 7^4+7^2+1 = 2451 = 57*43 = 2451  ✓

======================================================================
PART 3: THE FROBENIUS-COMPLEMENT PARALLEL
======================================================================

Two order-2 involutions in parallel algebraic structures:

  PROJECTIVE GEOMETRY            TOURNAMENT THEORY
  ─────────────────────          ──────────────────
  F_4 / F_2                      Tournament space T
  Frobenius σ: x → x^2           Complement τ: T → T^op
  Fixed field: F_2               Fixed set: SC tournaments
  σ has order 2                  τ has order 2
  F_4 = F_2[α] / (α²+α+1)      |T| = 2^C(n,2) points
  PG(2,F_4) = 21 pts            H-spectrum = {odd integers}
  Fixed pts = PG(2,F_2) = 7     SC: H(T) = H(T^op)

F_4 = {0, 1, α, α+1} where α² = α+1 (so α²+α+1=0 in F_2)
Frobenius σ(x) = x²:
  σ(0) = 0  (fixed)
  σ(1) = 1  (fixed)
  σ(α) = α+1  (moved)
  σ(α+1) = α  (moved)

Fixed points of Frobenius = F_2 = {0, 1}
Orbits of non-fixed points: {α, α+1}

On PG(2,F_4):
  21 points total
  7 fixed points = PG(2,F_2) (one Baer subplane)
  14 moved points = 7 orbits of size 2
  These 14 points form 2 more Baer subplanes (each of size 7)

On tournament space (n=5):
  C(5,2) = 10 arcs, 2^10 = 1024 tournaments
  Complement τ(T) reverses all 10 arcs
  Fixed points: 0 (no tournament can equal its complement)
  Instead: SC tournaments satisfy T ≅ T^op (isomorphic, not equal)
  8 SC isomorphism classes, 2 NSC pairs = 12 total classes

THE PARALLEL DEEPENS:
  Frobenius: PG(2,F_4) → 3 Baer subplanes (partition)
  Complement: tournament iso classes → SC + NSC pairs
  At n=5: 12 classes = 8 + 2*2 = 8 SC + 4 NSC (in 2 pairs)
  At n=7: 456 classes = 88 SC + 184*2 NSC (in 184 pairs)

======================================================================
PART 4: BAER INTERSECTION PATTERNS → CONFLICT GRAPHS
======================================================================

In PG(2,F_4), the 3 Baer subplanes B_0, B_1, B_2 partition the 21 points.
But the LINES of PG(2,F_4) intersect the Baer subplanes in structured ways.

PG(2,F_4) has 21 points ✓
Baer subplane B_0 = PG(2,F_2): 7 points
Fixed points of Frobenius: 7
Moved points: 14 = 7 orbits of size 2
Fixed points = B_0 ✓

Frobenius orbits of moved points: 7
Lines of PG(2,F_4): 21
Points per line: {5}

B_0 indices: [0, 1, 2, 5, 6, 9, 10]
Line-Baer intersection sizes:
  |line ∩ B_0| = 1: 14 lines
  |line ∩ B_0| = 3: 7 lines

BAER SUBPLANE INTERSECTION THEOREM:
  Every line of PG(2,q^2) meets a Baer subplane in either 1 or q+1 points.
  At q=2: every line meets B_0 in 1 or 3 points
  Lines with 3-point intersection: 7 = 7 = lines of PG(2,F_2)
  Lines with 1-point intersection: 14 = 14 = remaining lines

Finding all Baer subplane partitions of PG(2,F_4)...
Found 3 Baer subplanes forming a partition!
  B_0: [0, 1, 2, 5, 6, 9, 10]
       = PG(2,F_2) (coordinates in F_2)
  B_1: [3, 7, 11, 13, 18, 19, 20]
       (coordinates involve α or α+1)
  B_2: [4, 8, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17]
       (coordinates involve α or α+1)

======================================================================
PART 5: THE TOURNAMENT-BAER CONFLICT ANALOGY
======================================================================

CONFLICT GRAPH Ω(T) has:
  Vertices = odd cycles of T
  Edges = cycles sharing a tournament vertex

BAER INCIDENCE has:
  'Vertices' = Baer subplanes B_i (i=0,1,2)
  'Edges' = lines connecting points in different subplanes

KEY ANALOGY:
  In Ω(T): I(Ω(T), 2) = H(T) counts Hamiltonian paths
  In Baer: 21 = 7 * 3 = I(K₃, 2) * (number of subplanes)

  The K₃ structure in Ω(T) IS the Baer partition structure!
  Three 'subplanes' (K₃ vertices) each of size 7 (independence count)
  K₃ is the UNIQUE graph with I(G,2) = 7
  And 3 copies of K₃ IS K₃ itself (K₃ is self-replicating)

I(K₃, x) = 1 + 3x + 3x(x-1)/2 + ... let me compute properly
K₃ = triangle. Independent sets: ∅, {1}, {2}, {3}, plus NO edges/triples
Wait: K₃ has edges between ALL pairs, so max independent set size = 1
I(K₃, x) = 1 + 3x
I(K₃, 2) = 1 + 6 = 7 ✓

But the Baer partition 21 = 3 * 7:
  Think of 21 as I(3K₁ + K₃-structure, 2)
  Actually: I(3*K₁, x) = (1+x)^3 = 1+3x+3x²+x³
  I(3*K₁, 2) = 3^3 = 27 ≠ 21

  Better: I(P₄, x) = (1+x)(1+3x)
  I(P₄, 2) = 3 * 7 = 21 ✓
  P₄ (path on 4 vertices) factors as: (1+x)(1+3x)
  Factor (1+x) at x=2: 3 = Φ₆(2) = number of Baer subplanes
  Factor (1+3x) at x=2: 7 = Φ₃(2) = Fano plane size

THE I-POLYNOMIAL FACTORIZATION = BAER PARTITION:
  I(P₄, x) = (1+x)(1+3x)
  At x=2: 3 * 7 = 21
  (1+x) = Φ₂(x) evaluated at x, = x+1
  (1+3x) at x=2 gives 7 = Φ₃(2)

  But 1+3x = 3(x + 1/3) = 3Φ₃^{-1}(x)
  The root x = -1/3 of (1+3x) is the K₃ POISON ROOT!
  This root is 1/Φ₃(1) = 1/3 = the CONE RATIO!

======================================================================
PART 6: TOWER OF BAER PLANES AND FORBIDDEN VALUES
======================================================================

The Baer tower: PG(2,F_{2^{2^k}}) for k=0,1,2,...

  k=0: q=2^1=2
       |PG(2,F_2)| = Φ₃(2) = 7
       Forbidden H value? YES

  k=1: q=2^2=4
       |PG(2,F_4)| = Φ₃(4) = 21
       Baer partition: 3 copies of PG(2,F_2)
       Each subplane has 7 points
       21 = 7 × 3
       Forbidden H value? YES

  k=2: q=2^4=16
       |PG(2,F_16)| = Φ₃(16) = 273
       Baer partition: 13 copies of PG(2,F_4)
       Each subplane has 21 points
       273 = 21 × 13
       Forbidden H value? NO (too many graph types)

  k=3: q=2^8=256
       |PG(2,F_256)| = Φ₃(256) = 65793
       Baer partition: 241 copies of PG(2,F_16)
       Each subplane has 273 points
       65793 = 273 × 241
       Forbidden H value? NO (too many graph types)

  k=4: q=2^16=65536
       |PG(2,F_65536)| = Φ₃(65536) = 4295032833
       Baer partition: 65281 copies of PG(2,F_256)
       Each subplane has 65793 points
       4295032833 = 65793 × 65281
       Forbidden H value? NO (too many graph types)

WHY THE TOWER STOPS AT k=1:
  k=0: Φ₃(2) = 7.    Only 1 graph type with I(G,2)=7 (K₃). BLOCKABLE.
  k=1: Φ₃(4) = 21.   Only 6 graph types with I(G,2)=21. ALL BLOCKABLE.
  k=2: Φ₃(16) = 273. Hundreds of types. NOT ALL BLOCKABLE → H=273 achievable.

  The blocking mechanism is the K₃ AVOIDANCE theorem (THM-029):
  Ω(T) never contains K₃ as a component.
  At I(G,2)=7: the ONLY graph is K₃ → always blocked
  At I(G,2)=21: all 6 types contain K₃ substructure → blocked
  At I(G,2)=273: some types avoid K₃ entirely → not blocked

