  - The K₃ avoidance theorem makes I(K₃,2) = 7 unreachable
  - K₃ is the UNIQUE graph with I(G,2) = Φ₃(2)

======================================================================
PART 8: THE FIBONACCI-BAER BRIDGE VIA CYCLOTOMIC NORMS
======================================================================

Recall from MEMORY: F_8 = 21 = F_4 × L_4 = 3 × 7
And from Eisenstein norms (kind-pasteur S105c):
  Φ₃(b) = |1 - b·ω²|² (norm of Eisenstein integer)
  At b=2: Φ₃(2) = 7 = N(1 - 2ω²)
  At b=4: Φ₃(4) = 21 = N(1 - 4ω²)

The Fibonacci-Lucas identity at index 4:
  F_8 = F_4 × L_4 = 3 × 7 = 21
  F_4 = 3 = Φ₆(2) = Φ₂(2) = number of Baer subplanes
  L_4 = 7 = Φ₃(2) = Fano plane size
  Index 4 = |F₄| = the field that creates the Baer structure!

THE TRIPLE FACTORIZATION OF 21:
  21 = 3 × 7         (arithmetic)
     = Φ₂(2) × Φ₃(2) (cyclotomic)
     = F_4 × L_4     (Fibonacci-Lucas)
     = Φ₃(4)         (projective plane)
     = |PG(2,F_4)|   (geometry)
     = F_8            (Fibonacci)
     = I(P_4, 2)     (independence polynomial)
     = H_forb_2      (tournament theory)

ALL SEVEN are the SAME number, seen from different mathematical windows.

DEEPER: The Fibonacci sequence mod 7 has period 16:
  F_n mod 7: [0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 1, 6, 0, 6, 6, 5, 4, 2, 6, 1, 0, 1, 1, 2]
  Period of Fibonacci mod 7 (Pisano period π(7)): 16

  F_n mod 3: [0, 1, 1, 2, 0, 2, 2, 1, 0, 1, 1, 2, 0, 2, 2]
  Period of Fibonacci mod 3 (Pisano period π(3)): 8

  π(7) = 16 = 2^4 = |F₄|²
  π(3) = 8 = 2^3 = |F₄| * 2
  LCM(π(3), π(7)) = LCM(8, 16) = 16
  The Pisano periods at the Baer primes are powers of 2!

Fibonacci numbers divisible by 21:
  F_0 = 0, 21 | F_0
  F_8 = 21, 21 | F_8
  F_16 = 987, 21 | F_16
  F_24 = 46368, 21 | F_24
  Pisano period π(21) = 16

======================================================================
PART 9: THE SIMPLEX-CUBOID-BAER NESTING
======================================================================

Recall the user's observation:
  'An equilateral triangle sits in a square with two halves on either side.'
  'A tetrahedron sits in a cube with 4 halves around it.'

The volume ratios:
  n=1: 1-simplex in 1-cube
       Line segment in line segment: no extra pieces
  n=2: 2-simplex in 2-cube
       Triangle in square: 2 extra pieces
  n=3: 3-simplex in 3-cube
       Tetrahedron in cube: 4 extra pieces
       Ratio = 1/3 = 1/Φ₃(1) = CONE RATIO!
  n=4: 4-simplex in 4-cube
  n=5: 5-simplex in 5-cube
  n=6: 6-simplex in 6-cube
  n=7: 7-simplex in 7-cube

Extra pieces when inscribing n-simplex in n-cube: 2^n - (n+1)
  n=1: 2^1 - 2 =     0    |PG(2,F_0)| = N/A
  n=2: 2^2 - 3 =     1    |PG(2,F_1)| = 3
  n=3: 2^3 - 4 =     4    |PG(2,F_2)| = 7
  n=4: 2^4 - 5 =    11    |PG(2,F_3)| = 13
  n=5: 2^5 - 6 =    26    |PG(2,F_4)| = 21
  n=6: 2^6 - 7 =    57    |PG(2,F_5)| = 31
  n=7: 2^7 - 8 =   120    |PG(2,F_6)| = 43
  n=8: 2^8 - 9 =   247    |PG(2,F_7)| = 57
  n=9: 2^9 - 10 =   502    |PG(2,F_8)| = 73

  At n=3: extra = 4 = |F₄|
  At n=7: extra = 120 = |S_5| = |Aut(icosahedron rotations)| = 5!
  The simplex-cuboid gap 2^n-(n+1) connects to Baer at n=3
  because |F₄| = 4 is the field that creates the Baer structure!

Note: 2^n - (n+1) = Σ C(n,k) for k=2..n
  = number of subsets of size ≥ 2
  = number of 'interaction terms' beyond individual elements

  In the Walsh decomposition, these correspond to
  the Fourier coefficients at degree ≥ 2.
  H depends on degree 2 and higher — the 'extra pieces'!

======================================================================
PART 10: THE 1/3 GRAND UNIFICATION
======================================================================

The number 1/3 appears in AT LEAST 8 independent contexts:

  1. Φ₃(1) = 3, so 1/3 = 1/Φ₃(1)
     (reciprocal of cone polynomial)

  2. K₃ poison root: I(P₄, -1/3) = 0
     (the root that kills path independence poly)

  3. Var(H)/Mean(H)² = 1/3 at n=3,4
     (tournament variance ratio)

  4. Volume ratio: tetrahedron/cube = 1/3
     (simplex-cuboid nesting at n=3)

  5. Φ₆(2) = 3 Baer subplanes in PG(2,F₄)
     (Baer partition count)

  6. Parseval: 1/Σ|c_k|² = 1/3 for Φ₃(e^{iθ})
     (unit circle energy of cyclotomic)

  7. Cuboid-simplex excess: (2^n - (1+x)^n) / 2^n → 1 - (3/4)^n
     per-dimension factor: 1/(x+1) = 1/3 at x=2

  8. Eisenstein norm: Φ₃(1) = N(1-ω²) = 3
     (smallest non-trivial Eisenstein prime norm)

  ALL EIGHT are manifestations of Φ₃(1) = 3.
  The THIRD cyclotomic polynomial evaluated at 1 gives the
  fundamental constant of tournament theory.

